### **Ada Research**  Purpose and Aims		

With the increasing role of algorithms in our daily lives, there is a growing need to understand the binary operations of code and how it filters our world. Even if ‌digital resolution increases, the world seems to gravitate to the stereotypical. This is especially prevalent in ‌content in 3D libraries, apps, and platforms where there is a lack of diversity[^1]. The potential of algorithms is vast but the usage is predictable. Based on fixed taxonomies the reinforcement algorithm tries to keep us using the apps. The artistic research project Ada Research seeks to challenge this predictability by exploring alternative visions and expanding the understanding of 3D worlds.

Ada Research is a virtual reality (VR) world and a meta-quest into 3D computer vision. The name originates from Ada Lovelace, the world's first programmer, who wrote about the relationship between computers and generative art in 1842[^2]. The project seeks to explore ‌the digital margins and simulate patterns to help negotiate how digital algorithms create invisible fences. The project aims to enhance our understanding of how algorithms, as digital tools, shape our bodies, creativity, and subjectivity.

By creating an immersive virtual reality world that guides the player through a landscape of algorithms, the research aims to provide new insights into the hidden complexity of these mathematical constructs. This exploration describes and visualizes a world with increasingly complex control structures. With four ambitious work packages, the research starts with basic algorithmic concepts[^3] like noise and vectors and eventually progresses to topics such as generative reality and Artificial Intelligence (AI). Each package creates new game items, fantastical spaces, and game logic based on the algorithms researched. Over time the VR world gets populated with strange realities that the player is guided through. The game extends into anamorphic and exploratory spaces reflecting and negotiating the margins of the ongoing research. 

​​Central to the investigation is how fluid queer[^4] potential is coded. The world-building procedure seeks to show how complex algorithms, for instance, drag celebration and fluid simulation, inherently challenge us to find new ways to see the world. However, in the apps, applications, and platforms the binary stereotypes such as heteronormative gender beliefs and other cultural boundaries have a strong pull and content seems to gravitate towards the normative. The more algorithms increase in complexity, the more tools, platforms, and apps seem to take shortcuts. By recognizing algorithms as performative elements that modify different passages, the queer perspective can offer a critical lens through which to explore the power dynamics and social implications of algorithms.

The project draws inspiration from the history of art, particularly the utopian interplay between abstract and surrealist movements. It extends that relation by looking at the role visual thinking plays in mathematics and seeks in the margins to find hidden queer forms. Building on the margins of algorithms, the project explores the concept of entropy to hopefully find a queer ontology at its heart. 

The project is a collaboration between Konstfack, The Royal Institute of Technology Stockholm and Design Academy Eindhoven, and several individual artists. I will lead the project and produce new insights through artistic methods and exploration. To identify the margins the project manages a complex pipeline between art, science, and future industry. KTH will push the insights with deepening knowledge about systems and mathematics alongside DAE who also provides insights into the applied complexity of VR installations. This collaborative approach brings diverse perspectives and expertise to create a more comprehensive and nuanced understanding. The expected outcomes include the VR world, exhibited installations, a book, and a game wiki documenting the game and explaining the algorithms of simulations and geometry. The body of work is a fantastical world and a playground of joy, beauty, subversion, and exploration. ## Project description  Theory 

The goal of the project is to understand how algorithms affect the way digital tools and systems work and how they control our bodies and creativity. To help with this exploration, an investigation into complexity and entropy is central.

##### Queer Embodiment 

In the age of AI, digital materiality is algorithmic and performative. To embody this, I find great inspiration in the theoretical work and life of cryptographer and mathematician Alan Turing, as I find that different areas of inquiry intermingle in his work: entropy, questions of AI, mathematical paradoxes, spatial desire, generative queer morphology, topology and geometry, and queer joy and death. 

* Turing proposed the Turing machine, which laid the theoretical foundation for modern computers in 1936\. The Turing machine was an answer to the "Entscheidungsproblem," or decision problem, which questions the fundamental law of mathematics, and furthered the undecidable foundation of mathematics.  
* Based on the mathematics of entropy, Turing is known for cracking the encrypted messages of the Nazi Enigma in 1942, which helped the Allies win World War II.  
* In 1950, he formulated the Turing test, a test of a machine's ability to exhibit intelligent behavior indistinguishable from humans. Turing's concept of the "B-type unorganized machine," which he described in 1948, was a precursor to modern neural networks.  
* In 1952, Turing posed and solved the leopards' spots problem using mathematical morphology.  
* The same year, the UK convicted Turing of gross indecency due to his homosexuality, which was still illegal. He chose chemical castration over imprisonment, but the treatment made him impotent and depressed, and he took his own life in 1954\.

##### Entropy

The key to finding cross-connections between the points above is entropy, which simply put is a measure of disorder or uncertainty in a system, and a fundamental concept in thermodynamics and information theory. In information theory, difference requires more complex encoding than sameness. As we step towards more entropy, noise \- information, difference, and diversity increase. 

Hito Steyerl's concept of the poor image explores how images can be heavily compressed and disseminated quickly. Poor images are often of lower quality and may not accurately represent the original content, but they are still influential due to the reduction of speed of communication.  
Roger Penrose, a theoretical physicist, has suggested that the universe protects us from the inherent unpredictability of singularities by hiding them behind event horizons or margins. From Turing's cryptic letter "Messages from the Unseen World”[^12] Penrose argues that human thought is too advanced to be algorithmic and that consciousness must have a quantum physics basis that can escape entropy. The world must be abstracted and the process can risk suppressing elements that do not fit. 

In AI there is a trade-off between overfitting and underfitting. If a model is overfitting, it may be too complex and have a high entropy cost, while if it is under-fitted, it does not capture the problem at hand. The prediction of computer models has a complexity cost that goes to infinity and incompatibility. Behind the world of digital discreteness, there is a theoretical black hole. On the margins of a queer quest, the project seeks new comprehension. 

##### Misframing

Even if digital resolution/complexity increases, procedural algorithms are further developed and hybridization is possible, the world seems to gravitate to the stereotypical. John Law writes about Othering (2003), everything that is not independent, prior, definite, and singular, which refers to excluding or marginalizing certain groups or individuals based on perceived differences. Othering can lead to the suppression of diversity and the reinforcement of monocultures, which have low entropy and resilience. Judith Butler's theories of Precarious Life (2001) point to how some life is less valued, and Nancy Frasers writes about misframing (2008) \- certain issues or problems are framed in a way that excludes or marginalizes certain groups.

##### Algorithmic misframing

As technology strives to become natural and invisible, it often abstracts and simplifies complex processes behind interfaces, which can lead to the algorithmic enclosure of our social systems of knowledge. This enclosure is an expression of power that threatens the core values of democracy. Evgeny Morozov describes it as "invisible barbed wire" (2013), and Shoshana Zuboff as the "Big Other" (2015). In Algorithms of oppression (2018), Safiya Umoja Noble examines how algorithms and search engines can reinforce and amplify existing inequalities and biases. Atlas of AI: Power, Politics, and the Planetary Costs of Artificial Intelligence (2021), Kate Crawford writes about the hidden costs of AI and how AI damages the environment, fuels inequality, and shifts toward undemocratic governance. In a society controlled by technology, transferring control to simplified interfaces obscures reality.

### Time plan and implementation

The research consists of five work packages to be ‌distributed over the research period. All packages could build on the previous packages to create a truly queer game experience. It takes half a year to complete one iteration at a 50% activity grade estimated from experience and ongoing studies. VR game development is a complex process, from research to implementation and testing. This estimate means the project delivers two iterations per year and four major packages or releases during the first two years. In the project the last year is dedicated to optimizing the final release and making the final publication about the project. Here is the negotiable outline of the content of the four first packages.

* 1\. Basic Elements. Implementing the foundational algorithms that are essential for creating generative art, such as Randomness and Fibonacci. It could also include more concrete algorithms such as Perlin noise, Voronoi diagrams, sine curves and resonance frequencies, Sound experiments, and Particle systems to create basic elements of the game environment or objects ​​and build a solid foundation for more complex algorithmic exploration.   
* 2\. Advanced Elements. Implementing more complex algorithms that enable the creation of more sophisticated forms, such as Fractal subdivision, Flow fields, Fourier transforms, L-systems, and Cellular automata. This package also explores the algorithmic topology of desire and the creation of queer meshes and textures for instance in soft body simulation deformable objects, such as cloth, liquids, rubber, and ​​other simulation algorithms.  
* 3\. Pattern and World Building. Implementing algorithms that enable the creation of unique and dynamic patterns and game environments, such as Reaction-diffusion systems, Graph Theory, Procedural generation, Neural networks, Shading algorithms, and Evolutionary algorithms. How do we navigate an auto-generated world?  
* 4\. Advanced Techniques. Implementing cutting-edge algorithms, such as Swarm intelligence and Chaos theory and further exploring algorithmic life and AI. In this package, we also deal with non-euclidean spaces.

Each package will consist of an exploration phase, a workshop-test phase, and a documentation-release phase. As project leader, I will use Agile methods to manage communication and collaboration, receive feedback, identify any issues, and remain adaptable to change throughout each work package.
